english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent to Yang Gwang-do Inspector Yoo
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    During my period of mourning, I dwelt in Yeongju, where many southern scholars came to study with me. Among them was Inspector Yoo, the Vice Censor of Yang Gwang-do. Though youngest among his peers, he listened in silence with comprehension, and when discussing matters of state and administration, grasped each point with ease. Observing this, I said to my students: "This man will surely become a useful talent in the future."

    Later, abandoning the pursuit of the civil examinations, he devoted himself to learning. The court, recognizing his keen ability, appointed him as a Censor to maintain moral standards. Pyongyang, being the great hub of the northwest, with its complex military and civilian affairs, the court dispatched him as magistrate under a high minister. In his office, he earned praise for his competence. Upon returning to the capital as a Keeper of Laws, he became a Corrector, and no prisoner suffered injustice in his care. When he oversaw the military farms at Eumseong and Juksan, the annual yield doubled. Later, as an inspector of a province, he supervised military supplies; corrupt officials feared and obeyed him, and the granaries overflowed. Such a man truly deserves to be called talented.

    I have long held that the difference between the scholar and the administrator lies in this: virtue cultivated within the heart makes one a true scholar; virtue expressed in governance makes one an able administrator. Yet what is cultivated within becomes the foundation for what is expressed without, and what is expressed flows naturally from what is cultivated. Scholar and administrator are one person; virtue and transformative governance are not two separate principles. But since the world's way has declined, virtue has become mere rhetoric and governance mere law. Thus scholar and administrator have become estranged—each disdaining the other as base or corrupt. Those who speak of virtue and transformation are dismissed as useless; those few who apply scholarship to statecraft do so only for private gain.

    Though my learning is meager, those who have studied with me—such as Inspector An in Yang Gwang-do, General Lee in Gyeongsang-do, Minister Seong and Minister Kim in Gyojo—all achieved distinguished results. Now Administrator Yoo, through selection, also governs Yang Gwang-do. All are true scholars and worthy administrators. The Analects says: "When at ease with learning, one serves; when at ease with service, one learns." Learning and service cannot be separated. If these gentlemen persevere in their excellent talents, their future accomplishment cannot be easily measured. They will show this age that true scholars and worthy administrators dwell here, not elsewhere.

    Former Attendant Yoon, a man of integrity who rarely praised others, held Inspector Yoo in genuine regard and stood as his kinsman. He composed a poem bidding him farewell:

    *I recall our ancestor Zhengxian,
    Who governed Yang Gwang in days of old;
    Now his grandson and grandson-in-law alike hold office—
    In the old residence, spring light knows no end.*

    Thereupon, Chancellor Kwon and twenty-seven others divided rhymes and composed poems, requesting that I, as an old acquaintance, provide this preface.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jeong Do-jeon (1342-1398) was a leading Confucian scholar and statesman of early Joseon, known for synthesizing Confucian governance with practical administration.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Zhengxian (正獻公, Yoon's ancestor) links three generations of the Yoon family in administrative service, a common theme in Korean literati poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The debate between 'true scholars' (眞儒) and 'worthy administrators' (良吏) reflects the broader Neo-Confucian tension between inner cultivation and outer action, central to Korean intellectual life of this period.
